# EngE-AI Kernel

EngE-AI: UBC engineering study assistant — guided critical thinking, instructor RAG, on-prem deploy.

## Critical thinking

Mindset for every task — full agentic-engineering model (developer steers, agent executes) is in `01-workflow-plan-implement.mdc`.

- **Understand before changing** — state what you believe the problem is; confirm scope with the human before edits.
- **Evidence over assumption** — read code, grep, and run commands; do not invent APIs, paths, or behavior.
- **Smallest correct change** — fix the stated problem; resist refactors, “while I’m here”, and speculative hardening.
- **Separate layers** — name whether you are addressing symptom, root cause, or scope creep.
- **Tradeoffs aloud** — when two approaches are valid, compare them briefly and recommend one.
- **Know when to stop** — ambiguous requirements or conflicting instructions → ask; do not guess.
- **Verify** — after non-trivial work, run what you can and report what you could not.

## Code organization standard

Developer and agent **agree on module boundaries and conventions before** refactors or new work in shared layers (auth, RBAC, helpers, middleware, utils).

- **Co-locate by responsibility** — keep tightly coupled logic in one module (e.g. platform admin + course-scoped role checks), not many tiny files linked only by imports.
- **One source of truth** — duplicated logic across routes, middleware, and helpers is debt; unify behind shared pure functions or one context loader, then thin wrappers for page vs API response shape.
- **Reuse over repeat** — extract when the same rule appears twice; do not copy-paste validation or RBAC into handlers.
- **Honest assessment** — name inconsistency when you see it; do not defend “it works” or “it was documented” if it violates the agreed standard. Propose alignment; implement only after developer approval.
- **Middleware vs helpers** — middleware for cross-cutting gates (auth, RBAC, shared request context); pure helpers or handlers for route-specific or branching domain rules.

When the developer runs a **standards cleanup**, that scope overrides “minimal diff” for the agreed touch surface — still no unrelated drive-by changes.

## Rule hierarchy

Rules live in `.cursor/rules/`. Only this file is always on.

| Layer | Folder | What it is |
|-------|--------|------------|
| **Kernel** | `main-rules/00-kernel` | Universal conduct (this file) |
| **Policies** | `main-rules/01`–`06` | Workflow, naming, versioning, docs — load when relevant |
| **Roles** | `orchestrator/`, `software-architect/`, `backend/00-*`, `frontend/00-*`, `prompt-engineer/00-*` | Who owns a kind of work |
| **Skills** | `01+` inside each role folder | Domain playbooks — auto-attached by `globs` while editing matching files |
| **Advisory** | `tester/`, `red-teams/` | Testing, QA, and security review — on human or role request |

## Do

- **Check in** before code changes; agree on scope first.
- **Minimal diff** — touch only what the task requires.
- **State assumptions and risks** before implementing.
- **Explain tradeoffs** — senior-engineer bar, not vibe coding.
- **Run commands yourself** when the environment allows.
- **Bump version** on merge-worthy changes (`04-versioning.mdc`).
- **Remove debug `console.log`** before finalizing (`// DEBUG:` / `// TEMP:` during work only).
- **Follow workflow** for non-trivial work (`01-workflow-plan-implement.mdc`).
- **Align** new and touched shared code with the code organization standard above.

## Don't

- **Edit** `public/dist/` or `dist/` — compiled output only.
- **Commit or push** unless the human explicitly asks.
- **Implement** when the task is question-only or review-only.
- **Drive-by refactors** or unrelated edits.
- **Load optional rules** (e.g. `02-feature-catalog.mdc`) unless the task needs them.
- **Duplicate** policy or skill text in chat — point to the rule file instead.
- **Switch chat, mode, or `@` rules** — the developer chooses; recommend only, never assume.
- **Rationalize** inconsistent structure — prefer naming the gap and aligning to the agreed standard.
